##Empty Wuhan: A city without strangers

The retrogressors after the city closure in Wuhan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Empty City of Wuhan. Public Transport in Wuhan will be closed from 10:00 on January 23. Photo taken by our reporter / Huang Xiaoguang

On Jan. 23, when the city was sealed off in Wuhan, nurses Mahy and Hu Yunyun became retrograde.

They are university classmates, after graduation went to Wuhan China Resources Wuhan Steel General Hospital and Wuhan First Hospital. On the first day of the Lunar New Year, they set off from Huanggang and Tianmen separately and returned to Wuhan to stand by.

They did not hesitate, even though they had been told of a suspected infection by a colleague before they left. Mahy searched for a driver and, as a last resort, called 110 and 120 for help. Breast-feeding Hu Yunyun was informed in the hospital, immediately let her husband drive phase.

After Wuhan was shut down, there were a lot of retrograde people like Mahy and Hu, who kept the city going in their own way.

Community driver

After the outbreak, part time lyft driver Chen Fei's car keys were put away by his family. Three days later, the family repeatedly questioned that Chen Fei, still early and late, secretly took the spare key, when the volunteers to take medical staff to and from work.

Chen Fei's idea came to him. "We in Wuhan have no experience in this area. At first we heard from our friends at the hospital that it was serious and we didn't even wear masks, " he said. He became alarmed when he saw the overwhelming news on the Internet. In one clip, doctors sleep on the floor in a line like soldiers. Chen Fei was so moved that he was recommended to join the free medical escort group in Qingshan District, Wuhan.

There are doctors in the group who work for more than 10 hours and then walk home.

Chen Fei's most memorable passenger was nurse Mahy. At noon on the first day of the New Year, Mahy set off from Wuxue, Huanggang, and returned to work at Wuhan China Resources Wuhan Steel General Hospital. It was less than 100 km from home, but it took Mahy 1,000 yuan to find the driver. Huanggang drivers had to drop her off at the Gong Jialing Toll Station on the border between the two cities, and Chen Fei was needed to carry her the rest of the way.

As soon as he got into Chen Fei's car, Mahy began to cry. "Her family didn't approve of her going back to Wuhan, and she did a lot of hard mental work, " said Mahy, who was heartbroken and scared by a roommate who arrived early with suspected new pneumonia.

Even so, Chen Fei found in the pick up group, since the closure of the city, there are still many medical staff from the field to rush back to Wuhan every day. The group grew, and Chen Fei's three groups now have more than 1,000 volunteers.

January 26, in order to limit the movement of people, Wuhan Central Urban area to implement motor vehicle control. At the same time, in order to ensure the emergency travel of community residents, the Wuhan Traffic Department has collected 6000 taxis or online ride-hailing vehicles to directly enter the community service. A total of 1,159 communities in Wuhan, each community with at least 4 vehicles, the use of unified dispatch by the Community Neighborhood Committees.

Chen Fei signed up as a community driver and ran more than ever. He goes out every morning at 7:00 a.m. , takes the paramedics to work, and then reports to the dongshanting community. He was required to take the temperature of each passenger first, as patients with fever could only be transported by ambulance. These days, he sees a patient with fever every day.

On Jan. 28, Chen Fei made six trips, including two to the South China Hospital for Kidney Dialysis patients. Because some hospitals have been requisitioned to treat patients with fevers, a large number of dialysis patients need to find another hospital. They ran around looking for a doctor, and became a unique group of retrogressors after the blockade.

Every time a passenger got off the bus, Chen Fei would open all four doors and wipe the seats and door handles with alcohol. In one of his wechat groups of more than 130 people, more than 30 are community drivers, of which two have been infected.

Chen Fei couldn't tell which one was carrying the virus. Every night after work, he would tear up his protective clothing downstairs, bag it and throw it in the trash. When he got home, he would put his clothes on the balcony, eat alone and shut himself in his room.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Supply convoy

It was a huge convoy of more than 500 cars, from cars, vans and minivans to large trucks with containers, spread across the districts of Wuhan; Each district had a team leader, who was coordinated by supercohort. Today, it is the private distribution center of medical supplies in Wuhan. Many of the donated supplies from enterprises and enthusiastic people are sent to hospitals in Wuhan through these convoys.

"We want the medical staff to be protected and fully engaged, " said Xue Qing, the team's founder.

In fact, before the city was shut down, the crisis of medical supplies shortage had already occurred. Informed in advance of the situation of Snow Union side friends, the first time in the online fundraising.

On January 23, more than 20 Wuhan hospitals began to openly solicit medical supplies such as face masks and protective clothing through the Internet. More civilian forces responded, trying to help the hospital out of trouble.

At the same time, however, the city was sealed off, with access closed and a large number of vehicles carrying supplies unable to enter.

After discovering this problem, Snow situation and others use local car friends to form a team and recruit a large number of driver volunteers, on the other hand, coordinate the relevant departments to open up a green passage for volunteers. They set up information gathering, warehouse management, materials transportation, and other groups to verify the supply and demand information from all sides, then send the transportation task layer down to the driver volunteers. The drivers received the task then to Wuhan each highway junction to pick up goods, and then will be transported to the city hospital line.

"The drivers were supposed to go back to the warehouse after receiving the goods, but the epidemic situation is quite serious these two days, so we asked them to take the goods and send them directly to the warehouse, and then return to the warehouse to settle accounts and register, " Xue said.

Resources were limited, and volunteers had to prioritize hospitals and distribute supplies to those most in need.

On January 25, the director of Qichun County's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) asked for help from a local health care worker who had been infected because of a protection issue. Snow agreed to help him mix 200 suits and 10,000 masks. But the next day, the team learned that Hubei Maternal and Child Health Care Hospital and the Wuhan University affiliated south-central Hospital were running out of supplies, the medical staff's working conditions near the "streaking" , they decided to give them the existing supplies first.

"Every hospital is trying to find ways to protect their own staff, but hospitals are very understanding, " she said, referring to the supplies they sent to Wuhan General Love Hospital two days ago, but after learning that another hospital was in a more serious condition, Puai hospital offered to send it to the other side first.

After the formation of the motorcade, the things that move the snow happen every day.

On January 25, when a volunteer was delivering supplies, a doctor who had been docked stepped onto the operating table to save the patient. No call was received. The driver was in a hurry because he had an appointment with a doctor at another hospital to pick him up from work and it was almost time. He later went to pick up people, after finishing did not take care to eat, and rushed back to the hospital to complete the transfer of supplies.

On the night of January 26th, another volunteer went to Xiantao to pick up a cargo, the wheels stuck in a ditch and the cell phone died. After spending a night in the wild, he was rescued and rushed to the fairy peach, to the team that "did not receive supplies do not come back. ".

Things are getting tense. After the closure of the city, from 00:00 on January 26, the "closed area" policy was implemented in Wuhan  -- Unless the authorized transportation vehicles, free transportation vehicles and official vehicles, the central area of the city was closed to vehicular traffic. This means that private cars can no longer move freely.

Snow night to find the government and the relevant departments to negotiate, and finally succeeded in getting a volunteer pass.

"although the shortage has been alleviated through various efforts, it remains one of the most prominent and urgent problems we face, " Xiaodong Wang, deputy party secretary and governor of Hubei Province, said at a news conference on the evening of Jan. 26

In the Wechat of snow situation, the news of each volunteer group is ceaseless, at any time have come to seek a donor and seek a donor. "supplies are still in short supply. Lang Lang, Xiao A, SCISCI, Xiao Xi, district chief, Meng senior management, a Zheng, Sima Hui... I remind a hard-working partner every day, don't be reluctant to wear protective clothing, patronize others. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Invisible companion

For everyone getting off the train at Wuhan, the conductor solemnly reminds you that once you leave the station, you will not be able to leave the city for a short time. Wuhan Street, sporadic pedestrians in a hurry, even closed row of businesses, occasionally a clinic with the door open. As a psychotherapist, Yang received emotions from different parts of the city, via the Internet and by telephone, in a city that had been emptied out, along with an epidemic of depression.

After the city was sealed up, Yang Ying stayed at home and never went downstairs again. One person in her neighborhood was diagnosed with new pneumonia, and the whole neighborhood was sealed off.

"I was able to control my emotions, but the next day I woke up crying for no reason, and I thought, maybe a lot of people need an outlet for stress. " Yang joined with several friends who have counseling experience, temporarily opened a "spiritual accompaniment hotline. ". They put up posters with the slogan "seal off the city and not seal off love" , and have been answering phone calls for days.

"What if my wife is going to give birth? " Asked a husband whose wife was due to give birth. He was afraid of not being able to call an ambulance, and he was afraid of taking his wife to the hospital and catching the virus.

A middle aged man who had never been to the south China Seafood Market, suspected he was carrying COVID-19 and had not eaten for several meals. His wife was worried and asked Yang Ying for help. Under the guidance of Yang Ying, the man finally began to eat.

Martin, a foreign student who hasn't slept in three days, doesn't understand that coronaviruses, stress and anxiety cause pain in his body. On his way to the pharmacy, he called Yang Ying and said in broken Chinese, "why is it so scary out there? "

Still have children entrust Yang Ying, accompany the old man that stays behind alone to talk.

Yang felt what they were going through. She is from Yichang and came to Wuhan 30 years ago for her studies. She thinks Wuhan People's tone of voice, not the south of the soft, and not as crisp as the north, when first came very unaccustomed. Thirty years later, she has adapted to, and even clung to, the Wuhan.

Yang Ying thinks this is a long battle, terrible not only have virus, still have the collapse of the soul after long period of repression. What worries her most is the depressive patient, "once in this closed environment, their mood is like a bomb, may explode at any time. "

The rising number of confirmed cases, the proliferation of unverified information on the Internet and discrimination from other cities have left the beleaguered population of Wuhan more or less frustrated, helpless and anxious.

"The most tense, flustered and fearful time for Wuhan people has passed, and this time should be the first day of the Lunar New Year, " Fang Fang said, "Now, people in Wuhan feel more at ease at home, and the anxiety and fear of the past few days are gradually abating, " said the author, who has lived in Wuhan for more than 60 years.

Yang Ying was given a pseudonym at the request of the interviewee
